summary:
The provided literature shows that BTK deficiencies cause X-linked agammaglobulinemia through impaired B-cell development and antibody production, resulting in immunodeficiency—opposite to what would be expected for an autoimmune disorder. No studies indicate that BTK dysfunction or inhibition contributes to autoimmune conditions such as lupus or rheumatoid arthritis; thus, it does not play a direct or indirect role in autoimmunity.  

Final Answer: \boxed{\text{No}} 

Note: This summary focuses only on clinically significant findings related to whether BTK involvement occurs within established immune-mediated disorders involving autoreactive responses. It excludes non-clinical mechanisms unrelated to human pathology.

